---
import ProjectDetail from '../../../components/ProjectDetail.astro';

const rawBase = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const base = rawBase.endsWith('/') ? rawBase : `${rawBase}/`;
const img = `${base}images/RobotArm Images`;
---

<ProjectDetail
  title="Benchy Mover (4DOF arm)"
  subtitle="ME380 · undergraduate design requirement"
  date="Team of 5 · 4 months"
  images={[
    { src: `${img}/4.jpeg`, alt: 'Benchy mover arm – photo 4' },
    { src: `${img}/5.JPG`, alt: 'Benchy mover arm – photo 5' },
    { src: `${img}/6.JPG`, alt: 'Benchy mover arm – photo 6' },
  ]}
  customSections
>
  <div class="portfolio-stack" slot="sections">
    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <p class="portfolio-intro">
        Undergraduate ME380 design project: build a machine that can move 3D Benchy models.
        Our team chose design constraints centered on <b>precision</b>, <b>dexterity</b>, and
        <b>strength-to-weight</b> to guide sizing, structure, and integration decisions across
        a four-month build.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Design objectives</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Lift, transport, and place a minimum payload of at least 1:3 the weight of the
          entire robot arm.
        </li>
        <li>Complete the required Benchy pick-and-place cycle in under 60 seconds.</li>
        <li>Achieve repeatable positional accuracy under 1&nbsp;cm.</li>
        <li>Use only one approved power supply, drawing under 24&nbsp;V total.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Our design</h2>
      <p>
        The final direction paired a four-degree-of-freedom arm with integrated actuation,
        control, and mechanical structure tuned for the objectives above. Captions in the
        PDF summarize final rendered, unwired, and wired assembly views.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Main individual contributions</h2>

      <h3>Preliminary model & joint design</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Defined joint connections linking arm segments at servo joints in sketches, then in
          CAD.
        </li>
        <li>
          Established a consistent servo mounting template implemented across joints for
          integration alignment.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Elbow & joint connections</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Designed the elbow segment and supported shoulder segment CAD development.</li>
        <li>
          Tuned motor orientations for required range (including ~180° servo motion where
          applicable) and checked feasibility at each revision.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Miniature control unit</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Modelled a scaled control arm driven by potentiometers as an alternative control
          concept.
        </li>
        <li>
          Printed, assembled, tolerance-checked, and soldered wiring—later not used due to
          control limitations, but it informed mechanical tolerancing and interface design.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Base plate manufacturing</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Collaborated on counterweight strategy; implemented base-plate mounting features.
        </li>
        <li>
          Milled mounting holes and tapped to M3 in one attempt for accurate base integration.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Impact on outcome</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Standardized servo connections across the arm so downstream segments (including
          portions I did not own, such as the wrist) could reuse the same interface language.
        </li>
        <li>
          Reduced mass and complexity in joints and links to support strength-to-weight goals
          while keeping room for wire management features.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Technical summary (design process)</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <b>Preliminary modelling:</b> locked rotational axes, mounting points, and joint
          strategy before CAD solidification.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Elbow / shoulder iteration:</b> repeated assembly and stress-feasibility checks
          until a manufacturable solution.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Miniature controller:</b> validated print tolerances and motion intent; retired
          for control reasons but de-risked interfaces.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Base plate:</b> precise machining and tapping for a reliable structural anchor.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="portfolio-block">
      <h2>Learning outcomes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Stronger CAD + multipart assembly practice, including tolerances for clearance,
          sliding, and shaft interference.
        </li>
        <li>
          Better integration thinking across mechanical, electrical, and controls constraints
          (space, routing, and limitations of each domain).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</ProjectDetail>
